To give a short overview, of the major changes (again the Object REXX
.INF SHOULD have this change info in one place but doesn't):

- new syntax for sending MESSAGES to objects (3 flavors)
   ~ (tilde) sends a message to an object (use returned result)
   ~~ (double tilde) sends message to object (use object as returned result)
   [] (square brackets) send [] message to object
  By the way, the authors of Object REXX like to call the tilde a "twiddle"
  (yes, they like to say things differently on the other side of the Pacific)

- the syntax:
     object = something
  sends an "=" message to object

- A new set of "DIRECTIVES" starting with :: (double colons) are actually
  more like preprocessor directives similar to the "#" directives in the C
  language. There are four of them:

  ::CLASS starts a class definition
  ::METHOD starts a method definition
  ::ROUTINE starts a routine definition (not clear what the purpose of this is)
  ::REQUIRES identifies other source modules required (e.g. containing classes
   needed by the current source module)

- you can now use BRACKETS to create expressions in compound symbols. Example:

     say stem.[k+1]

  this used to have to be written as

     temp = k + 1
     say stem.temp

- DO ... OVER allows traversal of all tails for a given stem:
     DO tailvar OVER mystem.    /* each iteration will assign tailvar a new value */
       say "mystem."||tailvar "has value '"mystem.tailvar"'"
     END
   (I like this one, it was part of the ANSI REXX recommendations)

- Some new string functions:
    CHANGESTR() to replace occurences of one string with another
    COUNTSTR() to count the number of occurences of one string in another

- Some new SIGNAL conditions
    NOMETHOD for objects that are sent a message they don't understand
    NOSTRING for expressions requiring a string but given an object that has no
             string conversion
    ANY for any signal

- REPLY instruction to allow early reply to a message and continue caller and
  method simultaneously (allows concurrent execution of multiple pieces of
  REXX code). It does not appear that this uses OS/2 threads directly however.

- support for SOM and WPS objects (requires "importing" the SOM object definitions).

Most of the other changes are minor, but as you can see, Object REXX is
a MAJOR language change (before we even have an ANSI REXX standard).  To
be fair, it is claimed in the documentation that any "classic" REXX
programs will run unchanged under Object REXX.

